abstract: Candidates are promising a kind of change that history suggests they cannot deliver.

lead_paragraph: As the Democratic race for the 2020 presidential nomination heats up, a newly fashionable term has entered the political lexicon: “structural.”

abstract: Lower-polling candidates had their moments, but none outshone the front-runners, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren.
snippet: Lower-polling candidates had their moments, but none outshone the front-runners, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren.
lead_paragraph: Those hoping for an underdog candidate to run away with Tuesday night’s debate did not get their wish. The winners — at least in the initial assessment — were the night’s two front-runners, Senators Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren.

byline_original: By The New York Times Opinion

abstract: John Delaney, Elizabeth Warren, and the fight for the future of the Democratic Party. Plus: A chat with Charles Barkley.

headline_main: Boris Johnson, Democratic Party, North Korea: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: The candidates sparred angrily over whether to wipe out private health insurance and institute a government-run health system.
snippet: The candidates sparred angrily over whether to wipe out private health insurance and institute a government-run health system.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It took only one question — the very first — in Tuesday night’s Democratic presidential primary debate to make it clear that the issue that united the party in last year’s congressional elections in many ways now divides it.
